Thanks for the review! They were useful comments.
I (hopefully) addressed all review comments.

Thanks for your quick reviews! 
I don't see how to quickly do the 2 suggested generalizations, so let's leave them for a later PR.
I incorporated your last suggestion, reformulated docstrings with this change, and added a paragraph in the module doc explaining this.

:v: fpvandoorn can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).
bors merge

Pull request successfully merged into master.

Build succeeded:
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/9719110893/job/26828330870)
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/9719110893/job/26828330552)

It feels weird to have this in the MeasureTheory folder; this is firmly a statement in analysis, just like all Sobolev spaces theory. Maybe create a folder `Analysis/FunctionalSpaces` and put it there?

bors d+
Thanks!
I guess there used to be a `h2` here; you might renumber
Why?
It flags the hypotheses `hu` and `h2u` in the conclusion. But disabling the linter is not nice, I enabled it again.

```suggestion
```
"nope?"?
Oops, artifact from when the constant wasn't correct yet :-)
hs shouldn't be needed: otherwise, use the measurable hull of s instead. Since it contains s, it will also satisfy hsf
I also thought that, but I wasn't sure how to get `snorm f p (Î¼.restrict s) = snorm f p (Î¼.restrict (toMeasurable Î¼ s))`

Loogle tells me about [MeasureTheory.Measure.restrict_toMeasurable_of_sFinite](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Measure/Typeclasses.html#MeasureTheory.Measure.restrict_toMeasurable_of_sFinite)
I can replace `(hs : MeasurableSet s)` by `[SFinite Î¼]`. Do you think that is better? Both are true in my application.

I replaced the lemma, and this is actually nicer. I didn't realize we had to put some effort in making the set measurable when we applied it, so this is a nice simplification.

This does add a small amount of imports to the file `LpSpace`.
I have a proof removing the `SFinite` assumption, but I will first wait for #14260 to be merged, to avoid introducing new lemmas with a wrong name.
Could you sketch in the file-level docstring the proof you are following, first in informal terms and then describing the formalization concepts you use to avoid DTT?
Done, and I also further gave a proof sketch in 5 long proofs.
Whenever a proof is more than 15 lines long, I think it deserves some comments explaining what you are doing. This one qualifies.
Add some comments in the proof?
Do you really need the assumption that iota is nontrivial? Below, you assume `Real.IsConjExponent #Î¹ p`, which probably implies it? Same thing in the other statements below.

Well spotted! This removes multiple other arguments.
In `snorm_le_snorm_fderiv_of_eq_inner` I added a new condition that `0 < n`, and I *think* that is necessary, but my brain hurts when I have to think about 0-dimensional vector spaces.
As the statement is currently written, it looks like the constant may depend on F', while in fact it doesn't. Could you also quantify over F' in the statement?
Done. Note that in the versions with a finite dimensional normed space as codomain it does depend on (the norm of) `F`.

```suggestion
function `u` supported in a bounded set `s` in a normed space `E` of finite dimension
```
still needed?
In fact I think it's possible to get rid also of the SFinite condition, but I'll do that after this PR is merged.
The completeness assumption here is probably not necessary, but removing this can definitely wait for another PR.
Done in #14262

```suggestion
with Haar measure. There exists a constant `C` depending only on `E` and `Î¼`, such that the Lebesgue
```
I reformulated these sentences now that we've separated out the constants.

I have a small problem with existential statements like that, that the constant `C` might a priori depend on the universe of `F`. So you can not really write that "it only depend on E and mu" (well, it's true, but not what the statement says). I wonder if it's not clearer to define a constant `gagliardoNirenbergSobolevConstant E \mu := ...` and use that in the statements, to lift this ambiguity (with a shorter notation to be used in the current file, to make things readable). It would also have the advantage to avoid the ugly forall quantifier in the statement.

Same thing for the other statements below.

What do you think?

I am in favor, since I think that will be a lot nicer to work with in practice. I'm also doing that in the formalization of Carleson's theorem. I wasn't sure if that style was appropriate for Mathlib.
Since multiple statements in this file have slightly different constants, I'll probably use something like `lintegralPowLePowLintegralFderivConst`.
`irreducible_def`, maybe, to make sure that Lean will not try to unfold it given how nasty it is. Same thing for all the other constants definition below.
Can you say in the docstring what `e` is?
